			Ilene Gordon says Ingredion's customers
were ready for her team to help them.
		




What to do when your leading product becomes Public Health Enemy No. 1


\What do you do when your leading product becomes Public Health Enemy No. 1? If you're Ilene Gordon, the dealmaking chief executive of ingredient- and food-flavoring-maker Ingredion, you blow up the company and reinvent it. Gordon, 63, took over the top spot at the sleepy company then called Corn Products International in 2009. Among her first moves was shifting the company away from high-fructose corn syrup, a cash cow yet a much-maligned sweetener used in soft drinks, baked goods and processed foods. Then Gordon put in motion a plan to engineer the company's overhaul through a string of acquisitions, a change in strategy and transformation of the century-old firm's culture. Her plan is now bearing fruit, helping push its stock up more than 38 percent year-to-date on strong sales and better-than-expected margins. While her approach initially was viewed by some inside the Westchester-based company as radical and overly aggressive, few are complaining now as the profits roll in and its stock this year hit an all-time high. “Not only was she a visionary, she probably saved the company,” says Erik Gordon (no relation), a professor at the University of Michigan's Ross School of Business. “Whatever the facts are about high-fructose corn syrup, this fact is also true: High-fructose corn syrup is a lousy business to be in.” While Ingredion—whose primary function is converting raw products like corn, rice, tapioca and other plants into food ingredients—still sells the product, it represents less than 10 percent of total sales, down from north of 20 percent when Gordon took over. Her journey to diversify started in 2010 with the $1.3 billion purchase of National Starch, a Bridgewater, N.J.-based innovator in food ingredients and specialty starches that operated 11 plants in eight countries. That acquisition gave Ingredion a foothold in food textures, new capabilities in research and development as well as a new roster of customers. “We used the acquisition to really transform the company and refocus on putting together products that are very much on-trend,” Gordon says. The trend toward clean labels and niche nutrition “was all just accelerating in 2010. Back then, you may have had one friend who was gluten-free. Today, there are so many people who avoid gluten.” Gordon's timing, says Robert Moskow, an analyst at Credit Suisse, was excellent because it came as food processors and beverage companies were beginning to explore reformulating their products to remove artificial flavors, colors and other ingredients to meet changing consumer demand. “She deserves a lot of credit for having that foresight,” he says. Perhaps most important, Gordon used National Starch as a catalyst for taking a more proactive approach with customers. Instead of simply taking orders for Corn Products' legacy commodity ingredients, her sales teams were prodded to start asking what products its customers were developing and how the new Ingredion could help. “That's her greatest accomplishment with the company,” Moskow says. “She turned around the culture of a 100-year-old company, and that's not an easy thing to do.” Gordon says Ingredion's customers were “really ready to engage with us very early in the process,” and her team was prepared to help them start developing more healthful recipes “to meet this unmet market need.” The market has responded favorably. Shares closed Sept. 30 at  $133.06, up 454 percent since the closing price the day she became CEO. Today investors and analysts remain bullish on Ingredion's prospects as it moves headlong into developing new plant-based proteins, food colorings and flavorings, texturizers and other all-natural food additives to realign itself with consumers' preferences. Through its internal Idea Labs unit, Ingredion is working with packaged-foods companies to make their products more nutritious and more “clean label.” “Our challenge has been to figure out clever ways to use whole foods to replace processed foods,” says Tony DeLio, Ingredion's vice president of global innovation. That means adding color with carrots or beets; enhancing a product's texture with a fruit puree; or adding plant-based proteins to foods to make them more nutritious.
KEEPING LABELS 'CLEAN'
When a customer wants to remove an artificial sweetener or even an “added sugar”—under new government regulations, food- and drink-makers must disclose added sugars on labels—Ingredion can offer fruit purees that keep a label “clean” while adding the required sweetness. When a food manufacturer seeks to remove fat or sodium from a product, Ingredion's scientists work with a series of patented plant-based products to build texture and flavor back in. As a corollary to its relatively newly developed technical expertise, Ingredion is also getting more requests to help with nonfood products, such as improving packaging material by replacing plastic with a corn based-option or helping personal-care product marketers replace difficult-to-pronounce ingredients in body washes, shampoos and lotions with plant-based alternatives, DeLio says. “The trends of clean and simple, high-protein, gluten-free—all those things we're seeing here are becoming global,” he says. “It has presented us with a tremendous opportunity, and now one of the big questions is 'How do we invest for the future?' “ Best, perhaps, to leave it to  Gordon, who has turned a plodding old commodity company  into a growing high-tech innovation lab.


