7 References



Early years and education[edit]
Gordon earned her Bachelor of Science degree in Mathematics at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology in 1975, graduating Phi Beta Kappa,[4] and a Master of Science degree from the MIT Sloan School of Management in 1976.[5][6]
When she attended MIT, the male-female ratio of undergraduates was 10:1.[1] Her intention was to become a high school math teacher, but meeting other women at MIT who were preparing to become professionals led her to change her course, pursue a Master’s degree, and go into business.[2]
Career[edit]
After graduating from Sloan School of Management in 1976, Gordon went to work as a consultant for Boston Consulting Group. When the company decided to expand one year later Gordon volunteered to relocate to Europe.[1] She was a strategy consultant based in the Boston, London and Chicago offices, until 1980.[7]
From 1980 until 1982 Gordon worked at Signode, a packaging company specializing in materials handling.[7] In 1982 she joined the Packaging Corporation of America, a division of Tenneco Inc, where she had a mentor who advised her to go into management.[1][7] As the first female officer of Tenneco, she was the Vice President of Operations from 1994 to 1997 and the Vice President and General manager of the Folding Carton Business from 1997 to 1999.[1][8] Gordon’s worked at Tenneco for 17 years.[6]
